Out of the 39242 courses in the data set the Average gpa being a 3.41 is pretty good. While the average number of students in a class is 45 people, the class sizes are relatively small. The minimum number for a course is 100 which is the lowest to this day as well. With the highest being 750 I have yet to see a course with that high of a number.

bio_summary <- bio_df |>
  summarise(
    num_courses = n(),
    avg_gpa = mean(Average_GPA, na.rm = TRUE),
    avg_students = mean(Student_Count, na.rm = TRUE),
    median_students = median(Student_Count, na.rm = TRUE)
  )

econ_summary <- econ_df |>
  summarise(
    num_courses = n(),
    avg_gpa = mean(Average_GPA, na.rm = TRUE),

    median_students = median(Student_Count, na.rm = TRUE)
  )

bio_summary
  num_courses avg_gpa avg_students median_students
1         100   3.284        60.81            30.5
econ_summary
  num_courses  avg_gpa avg_students median_students
1         863 3.173812     54.87138              40

I notice that there is a significant amount of difference between the number of courses for the two classes. There is way more econ classes offered than bio classes. The average gpa overall is also higher in bio classes than they are in econ. While the average student count is higher in econ than bio. Median of students in a class is higher in econ than bio.

I notice that there is a significant amount of difference between the number of courses for the two classes. There is way more accounting classes offered than AIS classes. The average gpa overall is higher in AIS classes than they are in accounting. While the average student count is higher in accounting than AIS we can assume more people are interested in taking those classes instead of AIS. Median of students in a class is higher in accounting than AIS.
